<p1:Tab  xmlns="http://www.eclipse.org/xwt/presentation" xmlns:x="http://www.eclipse.org/xwt" xmlns:p1="clr-namespace:com.ifx.davex.ui.controls.app" x:Class="e" layout="{x:Null}">
	<p1:TabFolder bounds="5, 5, 600, 500">
		<p1:GTab text="General Settings" widgetName="General_Settings_TAB" visible="true" enabled="true" manifestObj="true" description="This tab helps to configure the required flash memory for EEPROM emulation.">
			<p1:GTab.control>
				<p1:Tab layout="{x:Null}">
					<p1:GGroup text="Data Size" manifestObj="true" widgetName="ggroup_memory_settings" bounds="7, 3, 291, 66" layout="{x:Null}">
						<p1:GLabel text="Data block size [Bytes]:" visible="true" manifestObj="true" widgetName="glabel_block_size" toolTipText="Allocate the neccessary size at the bottom of the flash for emulation." bounds="8, 29, 122, 19"/>
						<p1:GInteger x:Style="NONE" minValue="1" maxValue="8184" format="(com.ifx.davex.ui.controls.util.AppUiConstants).DEC" manifestObj="true" widgetName="gint_block_size" bounds="136, 25, 121, 23" value="2048" toolTipText="Set the required data size need to be stored in EEPROM." description="The Data block size defines the amount of data to be strored in non volatile memory. The APP allows to store a range of 1 byte to 8184 bytes into the Flash Emulated EEPROM . Even if the size can be configured from 1 to 8184, actual data block consumed internally may be higher. This is dynamically calculated, keeping 8 bytes for header for each data size configured and the next best value from the range [512, 1024, 2048, 4088 and 8192]. The datails of the data block size mapping is explained in the below table&lt;BR&gt;&#13;&#10;&lt;b&gt;Data block size vs Actual data block size Mapping&lt;/b&gt;  &#13;&#10;&lt;table class=&quot;URIList&quot;&gt;&#13;&#10;     &lt;tr&gt; &lt;td&gt;Input data block size&lt;/td&gt;            &lt;td&gt;Actual data block size&lt;/td&gt;   &lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&#10;     &lt;tr&gt; &lt;td&gt;(1-504) Bytes     &lt;/td&gt;               &lt;td&gt;512 Bytes &lt;/td&gt;       &lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&#10;     &lt;tr&gt; &lt;td&gt;(505-1016) Bytes  &lt;/td&gt;               &lt;td&gt;1024 Bytes &lt;/td&gt;      &lt;/tr&gt;                                                                                   &#13;&#10;     &lt;tr&gt; &lt;td&gt;(1017-2040) Bytes &lt;/td&gt;               &lt;td&gt;2048 Bytes &lt;/td&gt;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&#10;     &lt;tr&gt; &lt;td&gt;(2041-4088) Bytes &lt;/td&gt;               &lt;td&gt;4096 Bytes &lt;/td&gt;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&#10;     &lt;tr&gt; &lt;td&gt;(4089-8184) Bytes &lt;/td&gt;               &lt;td&gt;8192 Bytes &lt;/td&gt;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&#10;&lt;/table&gt;&#13;&#10;&lt;BR&gt;&#13;&#10;1. The block size is generated as below macro definition in the cofiguration file e_eeprom_xmc4_conf.h. &lt;BR&gt;&#13;&#10;&lt;B&gt;&lt;I&gt;E_EEPROM_XMC4_DATA_BLOCK_SIZE&lt;/I&gt;&lt;/B&gt;&lt;BR&gt;&#13;&#10;2. The internally allocated data size is generated as macro definition in the configuration file &quot;e_eeprom_xmc4_conf.h&quot;. The value defined in (&quot;E_EEPROM_XMC4_DATA_BLOCK_SIZE&quot; + &quot;8 bytes header&quot; + &quot;padding bytes)&quot; constitute the actual storage size.&lt;BR&gt; &#13;&#10;&lt;B&gt;&lt;I&gt;E_EEPROM_XMC4_ACTUAL_FLASH_BLOCK_SIZE&lt;/I&gt;&lt;/B&gt;&lt;BR&gt;&#13;&#10;"/>
					</p1:GGroup>
				</p1:Tab>
			</p1:GTab.control>
		</p1:GTab>
	</p1:TabFolder>
</p1:Tab>
